<section id="discipline" style="background:#D8EAD9;">
  <div style="padding:2.5rem 3.5rem 3rem;">
    <div class="section-label" style="color:var(--sage);margin-bottom:.75rem;">Discipline</div>
    <h2 style="font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif;font-size:clamp(1.75rem,3vw,3rem);font-weight:400;font-style:italic;color:var(--sage-dark);line-height:1.2;max-width:28ch;margin:0;">The cost problem isn't visibility. It's timing.</h2>
  </div>

  <!-- Card row -->
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr 1fr 1fr;gap:1px;background:rgba(90,126,94,.18);">

    <div style="background:var(--white);padding:1.75rem 1.75rem 1.5rem;">
      <div style="font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif;font-size:2.25rem;font-weight:300;color:rgba(90,126,94,.18);line-height:1;margin-bottom:.75rem;">01</div>
      <div class="discipline-card-title">The invoice is already too late.</div>
      <div class="discipline-card-copy">Commitments compound before invoices arrive. Architecture choices, vendor agreements, reservation logic — none of these wait for the finance team. By the time a report surfaces the number, the decision behind it is already old.</div>
    </div>

    <div style="background:var(--white);padding:1.75rem 1.75rem 1.5rem;">
      <div style="font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif;font-size:2.25rem;font-weight:300;color:rgba(90,126,94,.18);line-height:1;margin-bottom:.75rem;">02</div>
      <div class="discipline-card-title">Cost is a design input, not a report.</div>
      <div class="discipline-card-copy">The teams getting this right aren't doing more analysis. They built cost into the decision itself — before the architecture review, the vendor commitment, the roadmap sign-off. The report comes later. The decision doesn't.</div>
    </div>

    <div style="background:var(--white);padding:1.75rem 1.75rem 1.5rem;">
      <div style="font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif;font-size:2.25rem;font-weight:300;color:rgba(90,126,94,.18);line-height:1;margin-bottom:.75rem;">03</div>
      <div class="discipline-card-title">Finance and engineering need one language.</div>
      <div class="discipline-card-copy">When engineering and finance share the same cost model, decisions happen in one meeting instead of three. No translation layer. No waiting for the next sprint review to find out what something actually cost.</div>
    </div>

    <div style="background:#304D35;padding:1.5rem 1.75rem 1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;">
      <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:.58rem;letter-spacing:.16em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(212,232,214,.45);margin-bottom:.85rem;">What changes</div>
      <div style="font-family:'DM Sans',sans-serif;font-size:.95rem;color:rgba(212,232,214,.9);line-height:1.7;padding:.55rem 0;border-bottom:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.07);">Cost gets modeled early, before commitments start to compound.</div>
      <div style="font-family:'DM Sans',sans-serif;font-size:.95rem;color:rgba(212,232,214,.9);line-height:1.7;padding:.55rem 0;border-bottom:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.07);">Utilization becomes a core operating metric, not an afterthought.</div>
      <div style="font-family:'DM Sans',sans-serif;font-size:.95rem;color:rgba(212,232,214,.9);line-height:1.7;padding:.55rem 0;border-bottom:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.07);">Architecture decisions carry explicit economic tradeoffs.</div>
      <div style="font-family:'DM Sans',sans-serif;font-size:.95rem;color:rgba(212,232,214,.9);line-height:1.7;padding:.55rem 0;">Finance and engineering work from a shared cost language instead of translating after the fact.</div>
    </div>

  </div>

</section>



